                <div type="commentary"><!-- notes go here -->
            <p>Asellia Placida dedicated this epitaph to her husband, Decimus Ammaeus Pyladion.
                    The male form of this name, Asellius is found in several places throughout the Roman world, most
                    commonly in Narbo (CIL XII 4356, CIL XII 4627, CIL XII 4627), Pompeii (CIL IV 4311, CIL IV
                    7297a, CIL IV 7297d), and Rome (CIL VI 12512, CIL VI 22879). The Greek cognomen Pyladion (written in Greek, in CIL IV 7991 from Pompeii) perhaps suggests a servile origin, but whether  Pyladion was freed or freeborn is impossible to say. It is
                    unusual that his praenomen, Decimus, is almost entirely spelled out, with Decmo
                    instead of the more common abbreviation, D. The nomen gentilicium Ammaeus is attested elsewhere
                    in Rome at CIL VI 33686, CIL VI 37974, and NSA 1917, p. 296.</p></div>
            
        
        
